[96] The placement of genitives proves to be interesting. Usually genitives proceed after their attendant noun, in the fashion "article, adjective, noun," but in some cases there is some attribution to the noun. In the case of 15.5, this may be to signify that Hera *possesses* the chair, rather that presently *performs* the act of holding it. 

